It's those small acts of discomfort that mean the world to people as well as those big acts. Thank you Yes Theory, for using your channel to share stories like Xavier's.

snippet.textDisplay:
I know this might sound stupid but, I lost my cat a day after Xavier passed away... And for someone like me, who used to have severe depression and anxiety, my cat helped me a lot, and he kept me company when I really needed someone.
Ever since Chilly (this was my cat's name) passed away, I have learned to appreciate life in a different way. I have lost family members before, but I was too young to understand this, yet Chilly's passing really made me aware of how unpredictable and short life is, as clichè as it sounds, I truly understand it now.
And... Again, might sound stupid, but seeing Xavier really gave me comfort, because well... Chilly was a cat, he didn't have the means to tell me anything really, but seeing Xavier vocalize how he wanted to fight until his last breath, seeing that the love from his family members and friends kept him going, in a way was like getting a look inside what Chilly could have possibly felt too.
So, just thank you for this video. I hope it helps people realize the same life lesson that I learnt, and hopefully more people can start acting on this life lesson.

snippet.textDisplay: Okay so this really makes me emotional. My cousin has been suffering from severe depression for a long time. He wouldn’t talk, cry, or show any emotion at all. He always acts like everything is okay with him when it isn’t. When we were talking yesterday, I saw him crying for the first time in a very long time. I brought him to our school counsellor so that we could convince him to get admitted to the hospital so he could get treated. After trying to convince him for 3 hours we drove to the hospital. That was the first time he ever opened up and talked about how serious his situation is. I didn’t even knew my own cousin tried to commit suicide several times by running in front of a car, for example. And the worse thing is, that no-one noticed. He was able to hide everything so well that no one ever suspected anything. His own mom threatened him just because he likes the same sex. It just is so comical that when people like Xavier and the Australian guy try everything to hold on, people like my cousin just want to let go. I just want to tell everyone to keep on checking on their friends, family, or even just someone you know if they are okay and want to talk. Talking and telling your story can help. A lot of people are suffering and we can’t even see anything. I’m sorry for my rant.

snippet.textDisplay:
Thank's Man! My father passed away 2 years ago while my mother was fighting cancer. My father went for a normal check up at the doctor's and he ended up in the hospital. He passed away 2 weeks later, the doctor to me he was going to be okay and wait a few day's before I fly up to see him because of the drugs he won't know I'm there. That day I was going to fly to Alberta but after speaking to the doctor I held off. That night at 7pm I got a call from my sister and she told me my father passed away. It was heart breaking!! My mother beat her cancer, we kept telling her to be strong and don't give up!! Dealing with my dad's death and beating Cancer she's one of the strongest people I know!! Last time I saw my mother was 2 years ago at my dad's funeral in Newfoundland. We get to see each other this June at my son's Graduation, this is going to be the best week I had for a long time!!
Thank you for what you do!!
My thoughts and prayers go out to the family
Rest in peace Xavier

snippet.textDisplay: Liver cancer/diseases are unbelievably hard & painful. I'm facing a "lucky if I'll live 9 more years" since they found my PSC at the very onset... since I was diligent about my Crohn's immunosuppressive therapy. Then after my mom died I broke about a year after she died and I went into the psychiatric ward on purpose because I felt too "shakey" feeling like my personal "well 'o strength" was going dry. I learned about my well that year the doctors and ER didn't listen and I ended up finally being seen by my gynecologist who ordered a CT scan that showed the massive infection that was causing swelling in my spine, lesions across certain organs, and was some organs were shutting down. It took 3 major surgeries in 3 consecutive months to fix all of me telling those people that I was sick & that I was not mentally ill or imagining that I couldn't eat. Sucked then. I got diagnosed 5 years later with Crohn's disease but that's the way it likes to work. And at that point, I required another major emergency surgery cause I was eating a super high fiber/no oils & fats cause I got pancreatitis from gallstones... but it was really bad for my gut, and I didn't bounce back from that 4th surgery. A year later... they explained that I had Fibromyalgia. I know that I didn't have it before the shock of surgery to the body. I couldn't control my pain after that so I purposely went to a pain clinic looking for alternative therapy than drugs.  My aunt died from an accidental overdose so I didn't want to be on opiates but I somehow ended up on them anyway.  Eventually you become numb to everything so the meds can only effect everything else in your life as well.  But that's also the point where I put myself in the psychiatric ward to deal with things.  And I did. Got off them but as soon as I was stable, Life decided to kick me in the ass again.  Primary Scerlosing Cholangitis. PSC. It's a very rare autoimmune disease that is fatal.  Of the like 10% of IBD people who get it, something like 0.5% or 1% of that ten percent has Crohn's disease while the others are usually UC and IBS folks. I LOVE the fact.  It reminds me how special of a snowflake I am! ;-). So yeah.  I was given a time frame of 5-12 years.  PSC is so rare... it is on a special snowflake list of rare diseases at the CDC. But I ask for Disability and they said, nope.... cuz they do that to everyone who applies. But I know what I'm facing and I also know that I can fight for myself but sometimes, it isn't easy.  You get the Crohn's okay and the PSC stats... well they basically go up very slowly. I am not looking forward to the really painful future that's coming. Liver disease is STILL believed to be mainly caused by chronic alcoholism and drug use but in reality; it's caused by disease and illness. Plus no one wants to give a lobe of liver to someone who has a 12-15% chance of disease recidivism in the new transplanted liver. The immunosuppressive therapy is damaging (slightly) my kidneys. I was born with asthma and allergies then the stress of knowing something is WRONG but the doctor doesn't have the time... until a year of escalating monthly to bi-weekly to weekly to every few day visits til he noticed that I needed help getting down from the exam table.  I do wonder if I was like a "cash cow" since in his mind I was obviously a hypochondriac. Nope... he never listened.
